# Error Handling

## ZERO DISCRETION POLICY

These rules have no exceptions. There is no scenario - not a "simple"
case, not confidence the error won't occur, not wanting to keep code
short - that permits silently swallowing exceptions or leaking
infrastructure errors into upper layers.

Prohibited judgement calls:
- "I'll use `catch (e) {}` to keep it clean." - No. Log and re-throw or convert.
- "I'll let the Drizzle error propagate to the IPC handler uncaught." - No. Convert it at the infrastructure boundary.
- "I'll return an empty array on error instead of throwing." - No. Only return empty/null when 'not found' is a genuinely expected outcome.
- "I'll catch broadly with `catch (e: unknown)` in the use case." - No. Catch specific error types or re-throw.
- "I'll type the caught error as `any`." - No. Use `unknown` and narrow with `instanceof` or a type guard.

---

## Layer responsibilities

- `infrastructure/` - Catch Drizzle/SQLite errors. Convert to
  `RepositoryError` (defined in `src/main/application/exceptions/`).
  Log before converting.
- `application/` - Catch domain exceptions. Convert to typed result
  objects or re-throw as application-level errors.
- `ipc/` - Catch all errors from use cases. Log. Return a typed error
  response to the renderer. Never let an unhandled exception crash the
  main process.
- `renderer/` - Check `result.ok` on every IPC response. Display a clean
  message to the user on failure. Never show raw error strings.

## Standard IPC response shape

All IPC handlers return a discriminated union:

```typescript
// In src/shared/ipc-types.ts
type IpcResponse<T> =
  | { ok: true; data: T }
  | { ok: false; error: string };
```

The renderer always checks `ok` before accessing `data`:

```typescript
const result = await window.api.subjects.create(input);
if (!result.ok) {
  setError(result.error);
  return;
}
setSubject(result.data);
```

## Infrastructure boundary

```typescript
// Correct - catch Drizzle error, convert and log at infrastructure boundary
async create(input: CreateSubjectInput): Promise<SubjectDTO> {
  try {
    const [row] = await db.insert(subjects).values(input).returning();
    return toSubjectDTO(row);
  } catch (error) {
    log.error('SubjectRepository.create failed', { error, input });
    throw new RepositoryError('Failed to create subject', { cause: error });
  }
}

// Wrong - Drizzle error leaks to use case
async create(input: CreateSubjectInput): Promise<SubjectDTO> {
  const [row] = await db.insert(subjects).values(input).returning();
  return toSubjectDTO(row);
}
```

## Typing caught errors

TypeScript `catch` clauses receive `unknown`. Always narrow before use:

```typescript
catch (error: unknown) {
  if (error instanceof RepositoryError) {
    // handle known error
  } else {
    log.error('Unexpected error', { error });
    throw error; // re-throw unknown errors
  }
}
```

Never cast to `any` to access `.message`. Use a type guard:

```typescript
function isErrorWithMessage(e: unknown): e is { message: string } {
  return typeof e === 'object' && e !== null && 'message' in e;
}
```

## Domain errors

Domain validation errors throw `DomainError` (defined in
`src/main/domain/errors.ts`). These propagate up to the IPC handler
which converts them to `{ ok: false, error: e.message }`.

